1
00:00:00,001 --> 00:00:03,001
Domain management and understanding DNS records.

2
00:00:03,760 --> 00:00:06,760
In this lesson, we peek behind the curtains of the vast network of computers we call the internet.

3
00:00:09,700 --> 00:00:12,700
We'll learn about domains, DNS, how it connects your domain name with your hosting provider's IP address, and how to manage these settings.

4
00:00:19,640 --> 00:00:22,640
We will answer the following questions.

5
00:00:22,040 --> 00:00:25,040
What is a domain?

6
00:00:23,520 --> 00:00:26,520
What are DNS records and what do they do?

7
00:00:26,640 --> 00:00:29,640
How do you edit them and how long does DNS propagation take?

8
00:00:31,600 --> 00:00:34,600
Firstly, what is a domain?

9
00:00:34,200 --> 00:00:37,200
A domain name is the unique address people use to access your website on the internet.

10
00:00:39,600 --> 00:00:42,600
Like your actual address, anyone who wants to visit or send you a letter needs to know on which street you live and what's your house number.

11
00:00:47,880 --> 00:00:50,880
The web works similarly.

12
00:00:49,800 --> 00:00:52,800
People can type your domain into their web browser address bar or use a search engine.

13
00:00:55,800 --> 00:00:58,800
Domains consist of two, sometimes three parts.

14
00:00:59,400 --> 00:01:02,400
The name, the extension, and sometimes a prefix called subdomain.

15
00:01:04,520 --> 00:01:07,520
Here is an example.

16
00:01:06,000 --> 00:01:09,000
In the domain, WordPress.org.

17
00:01:09,000 --> 00:01:12,000
WordPress is the unique name chosen by the website owner and .org is the domain extension, denoting the type of website or organization.

18
00:01:19,200 --> 00:01:22,200
Meanwhile, in the domain learn.wordpress.org, learn is a subdomain associated with the primary organization that indicates the site's focus on educational content.

19
00:01:32,200 --> 00:01:35,200
Unlike humans, devices and servers communicate using numerical IP addresses.

20
00:01:38,000 --> 00:01:41,000
And that's where the domain name system or DNS comes in.

21
00:01:41,600 --> 00:01:44,600
What is DNS?

22
00:01:43,600 --> 00:01:46,600
The domain name system or DNS bridges the gap between humans and machines, translating human readable domain names such as www.example.com into machine readable IP addresses like 192.0.2.1.

23
00:02:01,600 --> 00:02:04,600
Imagine a giant phone book that stores all the names and corresponding numbers of every active website and online service in special text files.

24
00:02:11,600 --> 00:02:14,600
These files are called zone files and they contain the individual DNS records of each website on which server to find it, how to connect to it and more.

25
00:02:22,600 --> 00:02:25,600
These DNS records, unique to every domain, are grouped in a DNS zone.

26
00:02:28,600 --> 00:02:31,600
There are a few dozen DNS record types.

27
00:02:31,600 --> 00:02:34,600
Let's review the five primary records that are essential for your website.

28
00:02:36,600 --> 00:02:39,600
Number one, NS records, short form nameserver.

29
00:02:41,600 --> 00:02:44,600
These records tell other computers which server manages the information about your website.

30
00:02:46,600 --> 00:02:49,600
NS records direct the network traffic to where your website, mailbox and other online assets are stored.

31
00:02:53,600 --> 00:02:56,600
Every domain must have NS records.

32
00:02:56,600 --> 00:02:59,600
You'd usually have two of them, so if one nameserver is down, the domain lookup process can use the next NS indicated in the records.

33
00:03:05,600 --> 00:03:08,600
Why would you need to edit your nameservers?

34
00:03:08,600 --> 00:03:11,600
The most common scenario is when using one company to manage the domain and another to manage hosting.

35
00:03:15,600 --> 00:03:18,600
If you've purchased your domain at registrar A and a hosting plan at provider B, you need to connect the domain to your hosting using NS records.

36
00:03:25,600 --> 00:03:28,600
Here's how this usually works.

37
00:03:28,600 --> 00:03:31,600
Firstly, you find provider B's nameserver.

38
00:03:32,600 --> 00:03:35,600
It might look something like ns1.dns-parking.com.

39
00:03:37,600 --> 00:03:40,600
You copy them.

40
00:03:38,600 --> 00:03:41,600
Next, go to registrar A's control panel and find the DNS zone management section.

41
00:03:45,600 --> 00:03:48,600
And then thirdly, remove the old NS records and add the new ones you copied in the first step.

42
00:03:52,600 --> 00:03:55,600
Your domain will soon be connected to your hosting.

43
00:03:55,600 --> 00:03:58,600
Next, let's talk about A records, short for address record.

44
00:04:01,600 --> 00:04:04,600
It ensures that when somebody tries to visit your website from a browser, whether via a search engine or directly typing example.com, the browser would know which server manages this IP address.

45
00:04:13,600 --> 00:04:16,600
Once it has this information, the browser can fetch the files and display the website.

46
00:04:19,600 --> 00:04:22,600
If you're using your web host's nameserver, you probably won't need to set an A record.

47
00:04:24,600 --> 00:04:27,600
Your web host will do this for you.

48
00:04:26,600 --> 00:04:29,600
Thirdly, CNAME records.

49
00:04:29,600 --> 00:04:32,600
Think of the canonical name records as shortcuts for your website.

50
00:04:34,600 --> 00:04:37,600
These aliases let you point one domain name to another, which is how you would set up subdomains or direct traffic to a different web address.

51
00:04:44,600 --> 00:04:47,600
The most common useful CNAME is www.

52
00:04:48,600 --> 00:04:51,600
This record works like an email forwarder and ensures people can access the website whether they include the www or not.

53
00:04:56,600 --> 00:04:59,600
Alternatively, you can use a CNAME to direct visitors to a separate website, like the example of learn.wordpress.org.

54
00:05:04,600 --> 00:05:07,600
Next, MX records.

55
00:05:07,600 --> 00:05:10,600
The mail exchanger records handle the mailboxes of your domain.

56
00:05:11,600 --> 00:05:14,600
They specify which servers handle emails sent to and from your custom email addresses, including email forwarding.

57
00:05:19,600 --> 00:05:22,600
If you want to use your domain to send and receive emails, for example the email account info@example.com, you need to set MX records.

58
00:05:29,600 --> 00:05:32,600
Number 5. TXT records.

59
00:05:32,600 --> 00:05:35,600
TXT records are like sticky notes attached to your domain.

60
00:05:36,600 --> 00:05:39,600
They can contain all sorts of helpful information, like verifying your domain for analytics, services or optimizing email security.

61
00:05:44,600 --> 00:05:47,600
Here's an example of the latter.

62
00:05:48,600 --> 00:05:51,600
The next question is how do you edit these records?

63
00:05:52,600 --> 00:05:55,600
You can manage all these different DNS records via your domain registrar or hosting providers control panel.

64
00:06:00,600 --> 00:06:03,600
They interface changes from one company to another, but they all allow you to create, modify and delete DNS records and configure your domain according to your requirements.

65
00:06:12,600 --> 00:06:15,600
You might be asking, how long does it take?

66
00:06:16,600 --> 00:06:19,600
Whenever you make changes in your DNS zone, global DNS servers across the entire web need to update the records they have stored.

67
00:06:24,600 --> 00:06:27,600
This process of DNS servers updating their records is called propagation.

68
00:06:29,600 --> 00:06:32,600
Various factors affect the time it takes to complete this update, so expect anything from a couple of hours and up to 72 hours.

69
00:06:37,600 --> 00:06:40,600
Take that into account when you make these changes.

70
00:06:41,600 --> 00:06:44,600
You can check the status of DNS propagation on sites like DNS checker.

71
00:06:46,600 --> 00:06:49,600
Type your domain, select the record and test it across hundreds of DNS servers worldwide.

72
00:06:53,600 --> 00:06:56,600
We hope this short overview gives you a better understanding of domains and DNS management and helps you adjust some default settings to your needs.

